<div id="review_3166939590" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3166939590" />
    <a title="Warren Fournier" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/56665940-warren-fournier"><img alt="Warren Fournier" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1621886976p2/56665940.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3166939590?book_show_action=true">Jan 29, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Warren Fournier" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Warren Fournier" href="/user/show/56665940-warren-fournier">Warren Fournier</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/56665940-warren-fournier?shelf=horror-paperbacks-from-70s-to-90s">horror-paperbacks-from-70s-to-90s</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3166939590" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8679148338122720830">Fond memories still remain of me as a pre-adolescent lounging on the white sands of the Florida panhandle with my first beach read--&quot;The Night Boat,&quot; which also was my first McCammon book and probably only the third or so horror novel I had ever experienced. Maybe it was the whole package, smelling the salty spray of the Gulf waves while reading about the discovery of a sunken U-boat and its undead denizens off the coast of a Caribbean island. Maybe I had not experienced enough horror literature</span>
  <span id="freeText8679148338122720830" style="display:none">Fond memories still remain of me as a pre-adolescent lounging on the white sands of the Florida panhandle with my first beach read--"The Night Boat," which also was my first McCammon book and probably only the third or so horror novel I had ever experienced. Maybe it was the whole package, smelling the salty spray of the Gulf waves while reading about the discovery of a sunken U-boat and its undead denizens off the coast of a Caribbean island. Maybe I had not experienced enough horror literature to be jaded, and my young brain was still able to be shocked and titillated easily. But man, did I enjoy the hell out of this book.<br /><br />Thirty years or so later, I do recognize the flaws in the execution of this novel. I agree with the Lorn's 2017 review that it seems McCammon either got this imperfect and incomplete manuscript published on the strength of his earlier successes or it was chopped to pieces in the editing process. Regardless, it sure remains a great deal of fun. <br /><br />If you like B-grade horror movies and pulp fiction, and you don't mind wooden characters doing heroic things and saying even stupider things, this will be like comfort food for you as it has been for me.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8679148338122720830" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


