    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3346434776?book_show_action=true">May 27, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Randall Krekelberg" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Randall Krekelberg" href="/user/show/8657931-randall-krekelberg">Randall Krekelberg</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3346434776" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15288835500142903713">As with the first two, The Night Boat - when compared to others in the genre, especially at the time of its publication - is not just a solid horror novel, but is a stand out amongst other authors early works. Over the course of my readership of McCammon&apos;s work, I&apos;ve come to rate his work entirely separate from how I usually would many other novels/authors. Which is really, I guess, a round-a-bout way of admitting that I definitely have a biased opinion here. So, yeah, let this stand as a warnin</span>
  <span id="freeText15288835500142903713" style="display:none">As with the first two, The Night Boat - when compared to others in the genre, especially at the time of its publication - is not just a solid horror novel, but is a stand out amongst other authors early works. Over the course of my readership of McCammon's work, I've come to rate his work entirely separate from how I usually would many other novels/authors. Which is really, I guess, a round-a-bout way of admitting that I definitely have a biased opinion here. So, yeah, let this stand as a warning that this won't necessarily be the most reliable review "objectively" hahaha! With that said though, I certainly do think that - to look at this book completely from an objective perspective - this statement still holds true. But now you're probably thinking, well after that unsubtle admission, of COURSE he would think that. And to that I say, "touchè, doubter of God McCammon!"<br /><br />Simply put... This is a 3 star McCammon novel and, on the McCammon scale, that means: An unquestionably good piece of the cake, although probably best enjoyed as a snack between (or after) the other richer and thicker slices!</span>
  <a data-text-id="15288835500142903713" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

